<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from RSSB (SLC 016)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">RSSB (SLC 016)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Main points </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38pt; text-indent:-20.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">RSSB is owned by the rail industry but its governance and regulatory oversight ensures that it is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> independent of any part of the industry.  Its purpose is to support the industry to achieve their objectives of improving safety and performance and value for money across the industry.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38pt; text-indent:-20.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In its ten years of existence, RSSB has supported the industry in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e area of level crossing safety through extensive research programmes, the collection and analysis of data relating to level crossing incidents, the development of risk assessment tools and guidance and through international collaboration with overseas aut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">horities and research bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We publish extensive evidence-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">based material on the subject of level crossing safety.  Arising from this body of experience, we have three general points to put to the Committee before responding to the detailed questions furt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">her below.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Data published by the European Railway Agency shows that level crossings in the United Kingdom are the safest in the European Union.  Many studies have sought to understand international differences in level crossing safety and the overwhelming conclusion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from these is that the biggest determinant of level crossing safety is the level of road safety. It is also universally the case that although level crossings represent a reasonably significant amount of the total risk on the railway, they represent a very</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> small proportion of road safety risk. The United Kingdom has among the best road safety records in Europe, and taken together with the risk based approach to level crossing safety practiced by Network Rail and its predecessors, it is therefore little surp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rise that the safety record at level crossings is internationally recognised as the best.  The policy implication of this observation is that although there are likely to be reasonably practicable steps that Network Rail can take to improve safety at level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crossings, the largest contribution will always come from the efforts taken by road authorities and government to improve road safety.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As you will see in the detailed answers, virtually all of the risk at level crossings arises from the actions of member</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s of the public. Of that risk, around half is also the product of wilful acts while the other half arises because of mistakes or misunderstandings.  The rail industry can realistically make a contribution to address the risks arising from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mistakes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and misu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nderstandings, but is almost powerless to do anything about wilful acts – and this is where enforcement agencies come in.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Having said that, the nature of safety legislation, and the culture of continuous improvement mean that it is right for Network Rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">industry to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> search for ways </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to further improve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> level crossing safety, in more cost effective ways, and of influencing others who can impact on this from their own perspectives and responsibilities.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Are current safety measures at level crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">adequate? How should they be improved?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The majority of accidents at level crossings - estimated at around 95% of the total - are caused by errors or violations by members of the public in their capacity as road users or pedestrians. This is consistent wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h other European countries whose record in this area is tracked and compared by the European Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Agency, which has found the UK to have year by year the lowest or second lowest number of level crossing fatalities and injuries in the EU, normalised by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he number of train km travelled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is not, however, any room for complacency as every fatality and injury is a personal tragedy, and since its inception RSSB has been working with Network Rail and the road and rail sectors to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduce risk in several key areas. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the last 50 years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there have been three </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– though quite different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– major</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> level crossing accidents in which train passengers were killed, at Hixon (1968), Lockington (1986) and Ufton (2004) and the lessons learned from t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hese and other events are scrutinised and changes implemented </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  More recently Network Rail has been concentrating significant funding and effort in reducing the number of crossings, implementing improvements in engineering controls, educatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nal and public campaigns, and working with various agencies such as the British Transport Police (BTP) to improve the effectiveness of enforcement activities. Better evaluation of the effectiveness of such initiatives is also being implemented and closer e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ngagement with local communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, particularly schools,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is also important.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">In addition to bridges and underpasses what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replace or improve safety at level crossings?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail’s funding arrangements me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an that expenditure on level crossings is taxpayer funded, and so it is critical that measures adopted or even mandated are cost effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from society’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s point of view. Countries that seek to abolish all level crossing risk through widespread closure progr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ammes find that the costs far exceed the benefits and in almost all cases would be better off spending the money on other activities such as health services. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Establishing where it is justified to make</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> investment on building bridges or underpasses is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">important and RSSB has worked with Network Rail and the road sector to develop the AXIAT model which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">now</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">public road and rail costs and benefits to be assessed holistically.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> closing private crossings, particularly in rural ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eas, makes a smaller but significant contribution to reducing risk.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Understanding t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he most effective way of target</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing expenditure and effort is also very important.  RSSB has worked with the rail industry to develop the All Level Crossing Risk Model and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Level Crossing Risk Management Toolkit to allow individual crossings to be examined, hazards rigorously compared and improvement schemes identified. RSSB maintains the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">industry database on safety related accidents and incidents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> uses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">data and pred</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ictive modelling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">techniques to produce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the industry safety risk model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk reduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be examined and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prioritised. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Engineering improvements include the development of the radar-based obstacle detection level crossing system which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will allow level crossing controls to be implemented more cost-effectively as part of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the roll-out of its national Regional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Operating Centres</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, currently under construction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Network Rail is also introducing short lifting barriers at many of the few remaini</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng automatic open level crossings.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Educational activities include the very substantial investment that Network Rail has made in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">national TV and Radio advertising, targeting those most at risk from causing, or being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">victims of, accidents, but also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reinforc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing positive behaviour among the majority of level crossing users.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> RSSB is currently supporting the industry in examining the effectiveness of road signs at both public and private roads, and the wider issue of pedestrian risk at these roads and on footpat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h and bridleway crossings.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All these activities are contributing to the gradual but steady reduction of level crossing risks on the national rail network in Great Britain and RSSB would be happy to provide further information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  We also work closely with other European countries in exchanging information about safety initiatives and best practice and currently chair the European Level Crossing Group, and participate in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">steering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Global Level Crossing Symposium, which meets e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very two years, hosting it in London in 2012.  Planning is ongoing for the 2014 session in the USA.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should expenditure on improving safety at level crossings be prioritised in relation to other demands on the rail budget?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is the most sensitive s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ubject area. In an ideal world, public money would be directed at those areas that deliver the greatest benefit to the public – usually known as ‘value for money.’  The industry uses the criteria established in the Health and Safety at Work Act (1974) and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the EU Railway safety Directive to determine its safety expenditures – applying the principle of reducing risk ‘so far as is reasonably practicable.’  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Using these criteria across the board could lead to some reallocation of resources away from level cros</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sings because many of the investments that are being made are not justified on those terms – rather they are made to meet a target of risk reduction, or in some cases simply to enable a particular crossing to be closed. RSSB has produced guidance on decisi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on-making on safety priorities in the industry approved document</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">aking Safe Decisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(RSSB 2008</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which mirrors some of the wording of Network Rail’s certified Safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">anagement System. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s decisions and proposals on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evel crossing expenditure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> partly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recognition of the public concern which is expressed whenever an accident occurs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also because the risk comes largely from outside the rail sector, caused by people over whom the railways have no direct control. They are consequently diffi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cult - and expensive - to reach and to influence. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The number of trains on the network continues to increase significantly, so as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the current initiatives continue to produce results and risk is driven down further, it may become more and more difficult to j</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ustify and implement further improvements to address the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which will remain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  It must be noted that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">six </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ten </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fatalities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to members of the public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which occur </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at level crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">each year are spread across some 6000 locations, and as a pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oportion of total road fatalities they are very small.  However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">collisions between train and road vehicles at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">represent a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contributor to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the risk to passengers from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">train accident</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">less than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10%)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> so </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will always be a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> focus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n this area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given the comments in our opening remarks, the issue that we think should be addressed is whether the effort that is spent on level crossings by the rail industry is proportionate to the efforts taken by the highways authorities and government on campaigns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and investment to improve the level of road safety across the road network.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, if curren</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t research on improved signs at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">public road crossings proposes changes to traffic signs and the Highway Code, will the road sector contribute support and fi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nance or will Network Rail be expect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d to fund any changes?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Given that the rail sector is severely limited in its ability to directly influence road driver behaviour, a stronger ownership of the issue by the road sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would be more equitable and potentia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effect.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety at level crossings?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have dealt with this question in some detail our answers above, so the short answer is yes.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is Government policy and regulatory action by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level crossings adequate? What more should the Government and ORR do?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The rail sector has engaged positively with Department of Transport in an effort to give level crossing issues greater prominenc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e in the Highway Code and in the written driving test.  It is recognised that there are limitations to the amount of space / time that can be alloca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ted in the Code or during tests.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> excellent guidance for level crossing users produced by ORR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is available on its website but is not obviously accessible to most road users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – who are unlikely to be looking for advice from the railway regulator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  It is suggested that it should be made more widely available, and promoted more positively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by other agencies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ORR ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> looked at crossings both generally and at the individual crossing level and have perhaps not adequately considered the strategic view in terms of how crossings are kept up to date with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">changes to HMRI/ORR requirements/guida</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nce and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elimination of early Victorian arrangements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department for Transport could also do more to encourage collaboration between the highways/roads agencies with the railways to share the responsibility for managing level crossing risk.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">should the legislation governing level crossings be updated?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2008 The Law Commissions of England and Wales, and of Scotland, started work on identifying whether changes to level crossing legislation were needed, and if so, what they should include. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y specifically remitted work on public road signs to RSSB (which is in progress) and they worked closely with both road and rail sectors to agree proposals for change.  There was particular emphasis on the potential of the AXIAT model to help drive public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">road crossing closures forward, and the need for statutory co-operation protocols between rail and highway authorities. A number of dates for publication of a draft bill have been announced and have been passed, and it is suggested that this may be due to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a lack of political support for such changes.  Given that the existing body of laws is well out-of-date and does not help motivate all the various parties to work together effectively this delay is to be deplored.  It is hoped that the process may be resta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rted </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">RSSB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">expressed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concerns over one aspect of the possible changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that of the removal of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rossing Order procedure. Although this is intended to remove a level of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">government administration, it is also likely to remove a level of certainty that has served the railway well for the past 50 years. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">principal fear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is that it will become very difficult, if not impossible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to prosecute a motorist for an offence at a lev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">el crossing.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should public awareness of safety at level crossings be improved?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A number of methods are available, and some have been referred to already. Educating schoolchildren and other young people about the dangers present at level crossings is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">important and resources should continue to be allocated to do this, especially in areas near crossings.  There is a particular need to emphasise to the public that trains cannot stop as quickly as a car can.  Emerging research suggests that elderly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are also particularly at risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if they do not understand how to use crossings effectively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, so they need to be included as a target audience.  Finally, there is a definite need to make sure that road signs communicate the appropriate message, and when the cu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rrent group of research projects have been completed, it is hoped that DfT, and Parliament, will support any changes indicated.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Concluding remarks</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.25pt; text-indent:-20.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While the UK level crossings are demonstrably the safest in the European Union, it remains the case that it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is only constant vigilance and reinforcement of the messages about how to use level crossings, enforcement of the rules by authorities, and the never ending search for more cost effective ways of providing effective protection at level crossings that will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> maintain that position. In that respect RSSB is proud to play its part in supporting the industry in the way that we do.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>